```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    potentiometer [label="Potentiometer"];
    buffer [label="Buffer"];
    level_shifter [label="Level Shifter"];
    filter [label="Notch Filter"];
    amplifier [label="Amplifier"];
    anti_aliasing [label="Anti-Aliasing Filter"];
    daq [label="DAQ"];

    potentiometer -> buffer;
    buffer -> level_shifter;
    level_shifter -> filter;
    filter -> amplifier;
    amplifier -> anti_aliasing;
    anti_aliasing -> daq;
}
```

```Explanations
Potentiometer: This is where the pendulum's angle is converted into an electrical signal. A rotary potentiometer is used because it can easily be attached to the pendulum to vary its resistance linearly with the angle.

Buffer: The buffer is a unity-gain amplifier that protects the potentiometer's output from being loaded by the subsequent circuitry. It ensures that the potentiometer operates within its optimal conditions by providing a high input impedance and low output impedance.

Level Shifter: The level shifter adjusts the DC level of the signal coming from the potentiometer to match the input range of the DAQ. Given the pendulum's angle range of 45 to 135 degrees, with 90 degrees as the steady position, the level shifter ensures that the voltage output corresponds linearly to this range and is centered within the DAQ's acceptable range of +/- 7 V.

Notch Filter: To attenuate frequencies around 50 and 60 Hz, which are common power line interference frequencies, a notch filter is employed. It selectively attenuates these frequencies without significantly affecting the frequencies of interest, which are the swing frequencies of the pendulum.

Amplifier: This block is responsible for adjusting the amplitude of the signal to make full use of the DAQ's input voltage range while ensuring it does not exceed the maximum accepted input voltage of +/- 7 V. It can attenuate or amplify the signal as required.

Anti-Aliasing Filter: Before the analog signal is fed into the DAQ, an anti-aliasing filter is needed to prevent aliasing. Since the DAQ samples at 1000 samples per second, this low-pass filter eliminates frequency components that are higher than half the sampling rate (500 Hz) to satisfy the Nyquist criterion.

DAQ: This is the data acquisition system that digitizes the conditioned analog signal for further digital processing or analysis. The DAQ's configuration is fixed, so all signal conditioning must ensure compatibility with this system.
```

